3 Forward selection

Use leaps::regsubsets to implement a forward stepwise selection procedure with up to 21 predictors (why 21 predictors?). The response variable here is Salary which is numeric, so this is a regression and not a classification problem.

  • The model size (number of predictors) that minimises the BIC.
  • The model size that minimises the Cp statistic.
  • The model size that maximises the adjusted \(R^2\).
Code 
step_fwd = regsubsets(Salary ~., data = Hitters, nvmax = 21, method = "forward") 

step_summary <- summary(step_fwd)


# Extract minimum or maximum for each metric
model_summary <- data.frame(
  Criterion = c("BIC", "Cp", "Adjusted R-squared"),
  Value = c(
    min(step_summary$bic, na.rm = TRUE),
    min(step_summary$cp, na.rm = TRUE),
    max(step_summary$adjr2, na.rm = TRUE)
  ),
  Best_Model_Size = c(
    which.min(step_summary$bic),
    which.min(step_summary$cp),
    which.max(step_summary$adjr2)
  )
)

# Display a nice table
kable(model_summary, "html", caption = "Best Model Size Based on Different Criteria") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = FALSE)
Best Model Size Based on Different Criteria
Criterion Value Best_Model_Size
BIC -147.9169040 6
Cp 5.0093172 10
Adjusted R-squared 0.5225706 11

We can see that the forward stepwise selection algorithm has selected different numbers of features based on three indirect estimates of the test errors. Since the number of observations is greater than 8, and thus BIC penalises the model complexity heavier, resulting in the smallest model out of the three.

4 Lasso regression

  • Split data and fit
  • Inspect coefficients as function of \(\lambda\)
  • Check if model is sparse
  • Assess on the test set

Split the dataset into 60% train and 40% test (feel free to do this using either caret, rsample or manually). Perform a lasso regression using the glmnet.

Code 
set.seed(5003)
inTrain <- createDataPartition(Hitters$Salary, p = .6)[[1]] # Doing a 60% training split

# Convert to design matrix format
x <- model.matrix(Salary ~ ., Hitters)[,-1]
y <- Hitters$Salary

Plot the lasso regression coefficients as a function of \(\lambda\). Use cross-validation to find the best \(\lambda\) value (You can use the inbuilt CV function in glmnet - cv.glmnet). Support your answer with a visualization of the selection of \(\lambda\).

Code 
# set the range of lambda values to be tested. From the largest value of lambda to the smallest value. 
grid <- 10^seq(8, -2, length = 100)

# Set alpha = 1 for Lasso, alpha = 0 for Ridge and 0 < alpha < 1 for the elastic net
lasso.mod <- glmnet(x[inTrain,], 
                    y[inTrain], 
                    alpha = 1, lambda = grid, standardize = TRUE)

plot(lasso.mod, xvar="lambda", label=TRUE)
Code 
# Using the inbuilt function to do cross-validation
set.seed(5003)
cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x[inTrain,], 
                    y[inTrain], 
                    alpha = 1)

plot(cv.out)
Code 
# Get the best lambda
bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
[1] 2.208513

Inspect the coefficients in the best model above and check if there are any coefficients that have been shrunk to zero. The cv.glmnet function returns a list. Inspect the list and the outputs of the cv.glmnet function in order to find where the best lambda can be extracted.

Code 
# Extract the features for the best fit
best.betas <- cv.out$glmnet.fit$beta[, which(cv.out$lambda == bestlam)]
best.betas

We can see straight away that some of the features here have been converted to 0.

These are the coefficients that have been converted to 0:

Code 
# Shrunken betas (zero)
shrunk.betas <- best.betas[best.betas == 0]
shrunk.betas
 HmRun   Runs CAtBat  CHits 
     0      0      0      0

And these are the coefficients that have remained:

Code 
# Non-zero betas
non.zero.betas <- best.betas[best.betas != 0]

Using the optimal trained model predict the salary of the test dataset and calculate the mean squared error.

Code 
# Use the best CV model to predict the test set Salary
test.pred <- predict(cv.out, x[-inTrain,])[,1]
mse.lasso <- mean((test.pred - y[-inTrain])^2)
print(mse.lasso)
[1] 159812.4

5 Ridge regression [Take-Home Exercise]

Repeat the previous question with the Ridge. Perform ridge regression with the glmnet package on the dataset.

Code 
# Specifying alpha = 0 in order to specify ridge regression
ridge.mod <- glmnet(x[inTrain,], 
                    y[inTrain], 
                    alpha=0, lambda=grid, standardize = TRUE)

plot(ridge.mod, xvar="lambda", label=TRUE)
Code 
# Using the inbuilt function to do cross-validation
set.seed(5003)
cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x[inTrain,], 
                    y[inTrain], 
                    alpha=0)
plot(cv.out)
Code 
bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
[1] 498.4656
Code 
# Use the best CV model to predict the test set Salary
test.pred <- predict(cv.out, x[-inTrain,])[,1]
mse <- mean((test.pred - y[-inTrain])^2)
